1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,040
So today we're talking about a truly important research study that touches on a delicate topic,

2
00:00:05,040 --> 00:00:09,960
unconscious biases in Italian schools; we're going to see how stereotypes, even

3
00:00:09,960 --> 00:00:14,679
those we don't know we have, can have a real, concrete impact on the evaluations

4
00:00:14,679 --> 00:00:15,679
of students.

5
00:00:15,679 --> 00:00:16,679
Exactly.

6
00:00:16,679 --> 00:00:20,719
And the central question where it all begins is precisely this.

7
00:00:20,719 --> 00:00:25,960
Let's imagine for a moment two students, one Italian and one immigrant, who in a test, identical

8
00:00:25,960 --> 00:00:30,320
for everyone and, above all, anonymous, get exactly the same score.

9
00:00:30,320 --> 00:00:36,039
The question is, in the end, will their teacher give them both the same grade? Well, the answer,

10
00:00:36,039 --> 00:00:38,679
as we're about to discover, isn't that simple.

11
00:00:38,679 --> 00:00:44,200
Okay, let's start with the problem that researchers focused on in our middle schools:

12
00:00:44,200 --> 00:00:48,960
something doesn't add up, a difference in grades that isn't visible to the naked eye, a real

13
00:00:48,960 --> 00:00:50,679
hidden gap.

14
00:00:50,679 --> 00:00:55,240
Let's take a look at this graph, because this is where we see the heart of the matter.

15
00:00:55,320 --> 00:01:00,280
Here we see the grades given by teachers to students who, as we said, in national

16
00:01:00,280 --> 00:01:03,520
standardized tests, demonstrated the same level of preparation.

17
00:01:03,520 --> 00:01:08,599
The first bar, the slightly higher one, represents native students; the second,

18
00:01:08,599 --> 00:01:09,599
immigrant students.

19
00:01:09,599 --> 00:01:12,359
And the difference, even if small, is always there.

20
00:01:12,359 --> 00:01:16,920
With equal competence, immigrant students end up with a grade that is, on average, slightly

21
00:01:16,920 --> 00:01:17,920
lower.

22
00:01:17,920 --> 00:01:23,960
Sure, 0.14 points might seem negligible, but it's crucial to understand its real weight.

23
00:01:23,960 --> 00:01:28,200
This small gap, imagine, is almost as large as the impact that the mother's level of

24
00:01:28,200 --> 00:01:32,120
education has on a child's academic performance, and we all know how much

25
00:01:32,120 --> 00:01:33,880
socio-economic factors matter.

26
00:01:33,880 --> 00:01:36,680
In short, we're not talking about a meaningless difference.

27
00:01:36,680 --> 00:01:43,600
And so the question arises naturally: why does this happen? Where does this

28
00:01:43,600 --> 00:01:44,600
difference come from?

29
00:01:44,600 --> 00:01:50,460
To understand it, researchers tried to measure something very, very elusive:

30
00:01:50,460 --> 00:01:55,380
implicit biases, the unconscious ones of teachers.

31
00:01:55,380 --> 00:02:00,700
Exactly, and let's clarify what we mean by implicit bias.

32
00:02:00,700 --> 00:02:04,140
We're not talking about a conscious choice to discriminate.

33
00:02:04,140 --> 00:02:09,420
No, they are mental associations that trigger automatically, stereotypes that we breathe in

34
00:02:09,420 --> 00:02:14,140
from the culture we live in, and that can, without us even noticing, guide

35
00:02:14,140 --> 00:02:15,780
our decisions.

36
00:02:15,780 --> 00:02:21,699
To try to measure them, a test called the Implicit Association Test, or IAT, is used.

37
00:02:21,699 --> 00:02:23,420
In practice, it works like this.

38
00:02:23,420 --> 00:02:27,979
The teacher is asked to associate names like Fatima

39
00:02:27,979 --> 00:02:30,819
or Francesca with positive or negative words as quickly as possible.

40
00:02:30,819 --> 00:02:34,740
The basic idea is that if in our head the association between a foreign name and a

41
00:02:34,740 --> 00:02:38,860
negative adjective is more automatic, it takes us a fraction of a second longer to make the opposite association,

42
00:02:38,860 --> 00:02:43,060
the counter-intuitive one, like a foreign name and a positive adjective.

43
00:02:43,060 --> 00:02:47,500
That small delay, measured in milliseconds, is the indicator of implicit bias.

44
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:51,819
And the results, well, they were quite surprising.

45
00:02:51,819 --> 00:02:56,580
This graph shows us how negative implicit bias toward

46
00:02:56,580 --> 00:02:58,979
immigrants is distributed among the teachers tested.

47
00:02:58,979 --> 00:03:06,259
70%—a huge slice—showed moderate to strong bias, and only a tiny

48
00:03:06,259 --> 00:03:09,060
5% had none at all.

49
00:03:09,060 --> 00:03:14,580
Careful, this doesn't mean that 95% of teachers are racist, but that almost

50
00:03:14,580 --> 00:03:18,580
all of us have negative unconscious associations inside.

51
00:03:18,580 --> 00:03:23,780
Okay, once we measured this bias, the next question was:

52
00:03:23,780 --> 00:03:29,259
what happens if we confront teachers with these biases? Can knowing they have them

53
00:03:29,259 --> 00:03:31,699
change the way they evaluate?

54
00:03:31,699 --> 00:03:36,180
To find out, they moved from theory to practice with an actual experiment

55
00:03:36,180 --> 00:03:37,500
in schools.

56
00:03:37,500 --> 00:03:43,219
Experiment one: the design of the experiment was as simple as it was, I'd say, ingenious.

57
00:03:43,219 --> 00:03:46,419
They took the teachers and divided them into two groups.

58
00:03:46,419 --> 00:03:51,500
To the first group, which we'll call the "informed" group, they communicated the result of their

59
00:03:51,500 --> 00:03:54,539
bias test before they gave the final grades.

60
00:03:54,539 --> 00:03:58,259
To the second group, the control group, they told them afterward.

61
00:03:58,259 --> 00:04:01,539
The only thing that changed, therefore, was the "when."

62
00:04:01,539 --> 00:04:04,180
And the result was incredible.

63
00:04:04,180 --> 00:04:06,900
The mere fact of knowing their score in advance

64
00:04:06,939 --> 00:04:11,780
pushed the teachers in the informed group to reduce the grade gap by a full 0.35

65
00:04:11,780 --> 00:04:12,780
points.

66
00:04:12,780 --> 00:04:16,139
In practice, they almost eliminated the initial difference, and they did it mainly

67
00:04:16,139 --> 00:04:18,139
by raising the grades of immigrant students.

68
00:04:18,139 --> 00:04:22,740
At this point, however, the researchers wanted to go even deeper—that is, the

69
00:04:22,740 --> 00:04:28,660
question was: does knowing about one's specific bias make the difference, or would

70
00:04:28,660 --> 00:04:33,060
a more general warning like "be careful, biases exist" be enough?

71
00:04:33,100 --> 00:04:37,220
To figure it out, they set up a second experiment, this time online.

72
00:04:37,220 --> 00:04:41,660
In this second round, everyone received a general message informing them

73
00:04:41,660 --> 00:04:47,180
of the existence of biases in school; however, only half of them, the treatment group,

74
00:04:47,180 --> 00:04:51,980
were also told their personal test result in addition to the general message.

75
00:04:51,980 --> 00:04:55,939
The goal was precisely to isolate the effect of tailored information.

76
00:04:55,939 --> 00:04:58,980
And this is where it gets super interesting.

77
00:04:58,980 --> 00:05:02,379
Look at this table, because it's the key to everything.

78
00:05:02,420 --> 00:05:06,939
For teachers with low bias, the general message and the personal one

79
00:05:06,939 --> 00:05:12,500
had more or less the same positive effect, but the real surprise is in the row below.

80
00:05:12,500 --> 00:05:17,180
For those with strong bias, the general message was of no use.

81
00:05:17,180 --> 00:05:18,699
No change.

82
00:05:18,699 --> 00:05:23,540
They only changed their tune when they had their personal result slammed in their face.

83
00:05:23,540 --> 00:05:25,540
That's when they reduced the gap.

84
00:05:25,540 --> 00:05:29,420
And this leads us straight to the heart of the mechanism they discovered.

85
00:05:29,420 --> 00:05:32,259
What we could call the "surprise effect."

86
00:05:32,300 --> 00:05:36,980
Personalized information is a bombshell, especially when it catches you off guard.

87
00:05:36,980 --> 00:05:41,180
The teachers who changed their behavior the most were precisely those

88
00:05:41,180 --> 00:05:45,899
who would have likely said, "Me, biased? No way."

89
00:05:45,899 --> 00:05:49,019
And to confirm this, there's a striking piece of data.

90
00:05:49,019 --> 00:05:54,819
80% of teachers—eight out of ten—underestimated their own level of bias.

91
00:05:54,819 --> 00:05:58,420
This makes us realize how little we know ourselves from this point of view.

92
00:05:58,420 --> 00:06:02,460
And why direct, personal feedback can be so disruptive.

93
00:06:02,460 --> 00:06:04,259
And so we come to the point.

94
00:06:04,259 --> 00:06:07,020
What do we take away from all this research?

95
00:06:07,020 --> 00:06:13,140
And above all, what does it tell us about how we can make school a concretely fairer place for everyone?

96
00:06:13,140 --> 00:06:16,460
Let's briefly summarize the fundamental things we've understood.

97
00:06:16,460 --> 00:06:22,220
Point one: unconscious biases are not abstract thoughts, but have a real impact on grades.

98
00:06:22,220 --> 00:06:25,379
Point two: awareness is a powerful weapon.

99
00:06:25,379 --> 00:06:29,300
Telling a teacher "look, you have this bias" can reduce disparities.

100
00:06:29,300 --> 00:06:34,899
Third: it's one thing to say "biases exist," and another to say "this is your bias."

101
00:06:34,899 --> 00:06:39,500
Personalized information wins out, especially with those who have stronger biases.

102
00:06:39,500 --> 00:06:42,740
Finally, the true driver of change is surprise.

103
00:06:42,740 --> 00:06:46,139
The shock of discovering a side of ourselves we didn't expect.

104
00:06:46,139 --> 00:06:50,060
Let's close with an open question, a reflection.

105
00:06:50,060 --> 00:06:56,819
All this research seems to suggest that sometimes, to start solving a problem, you just need to make it visible.

106
00:06:56,819 --> 00:07:00,060
And the question we leave on the table is precisely this:

107
00:07:00,060 --> 00:07:07,699
Is bringing to light a bias we didn't know we had truly the first indispensable step toward defeating it?

108
00:07:07,699 --> 00:07:09,899
Thank you for following us in this analysis.